Part II - Environmental & Social Factors of Industrialization from 1990-2019.¶

by Catherine Taft¶

Investigation Overview¶

As someone who is a resident of two countries in different stages of economic development (US and Panama), I immediately thought to do something along the lines of development for this project. My initial interest was CO2 emissions levels, but I expanded my dataset to also include child mortality rates, GDP per capita, life expectancy and population density. These are all factors known to be influenced positively or negatively by the industrial and economic development of countries, and I wanted to examine any relationships between these to look deeper at the positive and negative impacts of development.

Dataset Overview¶

I worked with a dataset that I created out of five smaller ones, with the following categories applied to 180 countries:

  1. CO2 Emissions
  2. Child Mortality; 0-5 Year Olds Dying per 1000 Born
  3. Income Per Person/GDP Per Capita
  4. Life Expectancy in Years
  5. Population Density per Square Km

My goal then was to examine each of these factors of development and their relationships to one another.

Key Insight 1 - Carbon Emissions (Visualizations 1-3)¶

Visualization 1 - Emissions per Capita by Region 1990 - 2019¶

The first thing most of us (or at least most of us who are obsessed with climate change) think of when we think of industrialization is carbon dioxide (CO2) emissions, which are produced by fossil fuels. As countries begin to develop and industrialize, there is a significant increase in carbon emissions, so while this is a negative thing, it's also positively correlated with positive indeces of development like GDP.

The change in emissions over time really depends on development status. The wealthier countries (US, Canada, Europe) are in a position to start exploring alternative sources of energy or carbon cap and trade, and reducing emissions. Developing countries do not have this luxury, so while we see a decrease in the INCREASE of emissions, overall they're still increasing.

With the following line chart, we can see that North America (the US and Canada in this dataset) has dropped sharply after a very high peak, and the Middle East and Europe are also dropping their emissions. The rest of the world is increasing, though slightly.

Visualization 2 - US and China Emissions 1990 - 2019¶

The thing that intrigued me about that chart is that although the US and China are known to be among the world's most prolific polluters, East Asia is way down there in that grouping. So I decided to look at the US and China by themselves in a line plot to examine their individual trajectories and rates. Canada is also a high polluter on a per capita level, but still nowhere close to the US, so I just wanted to look at these two.

In this next plot we can see that the US and China have nearly exactly inverted trajectories. Keep in mind that these are two of the world's biggest polluters. As the US reaches its peak at around 2000, it begins a significant decline in emissions. Around the same time, China begins to really industrialize and modernize its economy and infrastructure, and sees a sharp increase in emissions, though that slows to ac rawl around 2012. At the end of this dataset, China is still only emitting half of what the US is, even after such a sharp decrease.

Visualization 3 - Global Emissions per Capita by Region 1990 - 2019¶

This area chart is also an effective way to demonstrate the proportions of emissions by each region. Each colored segment here represents the mean in emissions for each region over time. Again we see North America just dominating. The Middle East is also a significant polluter, due to their growing population's intense energy needs living in such a hot climate. There are other countries in very hot climates who have lower emissions, but due to oil wealth, many Middle Eastern countries have the money to provide this energy infrastructure to their whole populations.

Key Insight 2 - Life Expectancy Increases, Child Mortality Decreases (Visualizations 4-¶

Visualization 4 - Life Expectancy by Region 1990 and 2019¶

It follows logic that as countries grow wealthier, as technology and access to technology increases, as employment opportunities expand along with increased industry, as healthcare advances and countries grow their healthcare infrastructure as development proceeds, life expectancy will go up and child mortality will go down. The first of these that I looked at was just the comparison of life expectancy across regions in 1990, against 2019. In general we saw fairly modest if not small increases (due to decent life expectancies already in 1990), with the exception of Sub-Saharan Africa and South Asia, which saw very large increases.

Visualization 5 - Child Mortality By Region 1990 and 2019¶

Then I chose to look at the other side of that coin, which is child mortality rates. I was expecting a decrease of similar proportion to the increase in life expectancy, but I was actually really surprised by the enormous decrease in every region except North America and to a lesser extent Europe, which already had comparatively low rates. In particular the two regions with substantial increases in life expectancy, South Asia and Sub Saharan Africa, show just a stunning drop in child mortality. SS Africa still has a significant level but it's less than half of what it was. It really made me happy to see this.

Visualization 6 - Emissions Against GDP Per Capita, Size as Life Expectancy¶

As mentioned previously, despite emissions being a negative thing for the environment, they are a metric for economic growth. Next we have a scatterplot comparing emissions to GDP per capita for three regions: Europe & Central Asia, the Middle East & North Africa, and South Asia. Each region is color coded according to the legend. We see a positive correlation between emissions and GDP, but I've also added life expectancy as a third variable, represented by point size. The larger the point, the greater the life expectancy. In general there is not a huge range in life expectancies, but we do see an increase as we move up in GDP, which of course means we're also moving up in emissions. The biggest range actually seems to be in Europe/Central Asia.

Visualization 7 - Emissions and GDP against Child Mortality Rate¶

When doing bivariate comparisons, child mortality didn't really make sense against any of the variables. The plot I got for it against GDP was strange and hard to interpret. So I chose to revisit that as a third variable against two others that I know to have a correlation, emissions and GDP. And indeed now we can see a more distinct relationship. The higher rates of child mortality are clustered around the low emissions and low GDP area, which indicates that less developed countries have higher child mortality. There is a dark strip that extends upwards over the cluster, which corresponds to some of the European countries with low life expectancies that we saw in the previous visualization.

Key Insight 3 - Wealth inequality has increased drastically¶

Visualization 8 - GDP per Capita Across Regions 1990 - 2019¶

The final visualization is a violin plot depicting changes in GDP per capita between 1990 and 2019 across all regions. The thing here that stands out is that in all cases in the 2019 data, it is not clustered around the median anywhere near as much as it was in 1990. We see the movement of the interquartile range in the expansion of the 3rd quartile, and the min/max expand in both directions. It very clearly reinforces the idea that the middle class is being eroded in favor of creating richer and poorer people.

Summary¶

In summary, what we've seen is that as the world is in a state of rapid industrialization and economic expansion, the metrics associated with that have rapidly begun to shift. The primary of these is the CO2 emissions levels, but correlated with that are increases in GDP per capita and life expectancy, as well as a decrease in child mortality across the world. However, disturbingly, we can also see a huge increase in wealth inequality. My concern is that as wealth is siloed at the top, some of the problems that haunted society in its less developed state, particularly around poor health outcomes, may return to certain segments of society even in developed countries.

It's worth noting some limitations in these datasets. Some economically significant territories like Taiwan were dropped because they were not featured in all datasets. Also, some of the regions were segmented by the authors of the datasets according to geopolitical or cultural commonalities (i.e. Latin America, Caribbean) rather than in their complete geographic designation. So for example, North America did not include the Caribbean or Central America as it should. However there is value there as well, since cultural and political ties often influence development more than geographic location.
